# Troubleshooting Notes

---

## 2026-03-17 — Keyboard dead on lock + kernel panic on suspend

### Symptoms
- Physical keyboard unresponsive when hyprlock appeared before sleep
- Machine rebooted instead of suspending (~08:40)

### Root cause

Two separate but related issues:

**1. Kernel oops caused reboot**

At 08:40:03, `suspend-fix-t2.service` ran `rmmod -f apple-bce` while pipewire still
held an open ALSA PCM handle to the T2 audio device (`hw:0,0p`). Pipewire tried to
call `snd_pcm_drop` to close the stream, but the MMIO region backing `apple-bce` was
already unmapped, causing a page fault:

  BUG: unable to handle page fault for address: ffffd0ac8654404c
  Oops: 0002 [#1] SMP NOPTI
  Tainted: [R]=FORCED_RMMOD, [C]=CRAP
  RIP: iowrite32
  Call trace: aaudio_pcm_trigger → aaudio_cmd_stop_io → __aaudio_send_cmd_sync

The `aaudio` module (part of `apple_bce`) was not unloaded before `apple-bce` itself,
so `rmmod -f` was required and caused the crash. speech-dispatcher had initialized a
pipewire connection to the T2 audio device at 08:04 and left it open.

**2. Keyboard dead during hyprlock**

`hypridle`'s `before_sleep_cmd = pidof hyprlock || hyprlock` runs concurrently with
`suspend-fix-t2.service` (both triggered at sleep.target). By the time hyprlock
appeared on screen, `apple-bce` (keyboard driver) was already unloaded.

### Fix

**suspend-fix-t2.service** — unload `aaudio` before `apple-bce` so force-removal
is not needed:

  # Before (broken):
  ExecStart=-/usr/bin/rmmod -f hid_appletb_kbd hid_appletb_bl
  ExecStart=-/usr/bin/rmmod -f apple-bce

  # After:
  ExecStart=-/usr/bin/modprobe -r hid_appletb_kbd hid_appletb_bl
  ExecStart=-/usr/bin/modprobe -r aaudio
  ExecStart=-/usr/bin/modprobe -r apple-bce

  # On resume, reload aaudio after apple-bce:
  ExecStop=/usr/bin/modprobe apple-bce
  ExecStop=/usr/bin/sleep 2
  ExecStop=/usr/bin/modprobe aaudio
  ExecStop=/usr/bin/modprobe hid_appletb_bl
  ExecStop=/usr/bin/modprobe hid_appletb_kbd

**~/.config/hypr/hypridle.conf** — remove `before_sleep_cmd` (races with keyboard
unload); add hyprlock to `after_sleep_cmd` to lock on resume for early-suspend case:

  # Before:
  general {
      lock_cmd = pidof hyprlock || hyprlock
      before_sleep_cmd = pidof hyprlock || hyprlock
      after_sleep_cmd = hyprctl dispatch dpms on
  }

  # After:
  general {
      lock_cmd = pidof hyprlock || hyprlock
      after_sleep_cmd = hyprctl dispatch dpms on; pidof hyprlock || hyprlock
  }

  Normal idle path: hyprlock starts at 180s → keyboard still alive → suspend at
  600s → on resume hyprlock is already showing.
  Early suspend path: no pre-sleep lock, but locks immediately on resume.

### Relevant log commands

  # View the crash:
  journalctl -b -1 --no-pager --since "2026-03-17 08:38:00" --until "2026-03-17 08:43:15" | grep -v UFW

  # Check suspend-fix-t2 service status:
  systemctl status suspend-fix-t2.service

  # Watch pipewire clients before suspend:
  pw-top
